Lam Research sits in the spotlight after a series of analyst price target changes, with individual moves ranging from US$6 to US$105 per share. These shifts come as research firms reassess wafer fab equipment demand, earnings potential and how much investors might be willing to pay. This is highlighted by actions such as BofA adding Lam Research to its US 1 List, while others maintain more cautious stances. As you read on, you will see how these evolving targets shape the broader story and what to watch as the narrative develops.
Stay updated as the Fair Value for Lam Research shifts by adding it to your watchlist or portfolio. Alternatively, explore our Community to discover new perspectives on Lam Research.
BofA highlighted Lam Research by adding the stock to its US 1 List, grouping it with what the firm describes as its best investment ideas. This signals strong confidence in execution and long term earnings potential.
Multiple firms, including Morgan Stanley, Barclays, Goldman Sachs, Citi, Susquehanna, Oppenheimer, TD Cowen, Stifel, B. Riley, Deutsche Bank and Argus, raised their Lam Research price targets, reflecting more constructive views on wafer fab equipment demand, especially around DRAM and advanced packaging.
Barclays and Morgan Stanley referenced a robust investment environment for wafer fab equipment and updated market growth forecasts. This supports the case that Lam Research could benefit if those industry expectations play out.
Erste Group downgraded Lam Research, suggesting some concern that execution, valuation or industry expectations may already embed a lot of optimism even as other firms raise their targets.
Several firms, such as Morgan Stanley and Barclays, kept Equal Weight type ratings alongside higher targets. For these analysts, risk and reward appear more balanced than outright bullish.
Do your thoughts align with the Bull or Bear Analysts? Perhaps you think there's more to the story. Head to the Simply Wall St Community to discover more perspectives!
We've flagged 1 risk for Lam Research. See which could impact your investment.
The U.S. government ordered a pause on certain chip equipment sales to Chinese chipmaker Hua Hong, adding another regulatory data point for U.S. wafer fab equipment suppliers with exposure to China related demand.
Micron urged U.S. authorities to further restrict chip tool sales to China, keeping export controls and access to Chinese customers in focus for U.S. equipment makers.
Reports indicated that BE Semiconductor is reviewing takeover interest from potential buyers, with Lam Research cited among possible suitors alongside Applied Materials, which already holds a 9% stake in BE Semi.
Media coverage pointed to communication between Elon Musk's team and chip suppliers around a Terafab concept, highlighting ongoing attention on high performance computing and the related chip supply chain.
Fair Value in the model is set at US$309.52 per share, compared with the prior US$280.90.
Revenue Growth assumption is set at 19.05%, compared with the prior 17.90%.
Net Profit Margin assumption is set at 33.74%, compared with the prior 31.53%.
Future P/E multiple is set at 39.55x, compared with the prior 41.45x.
Discount Rate is set at 10.53%, compared with the prior 10.52%.
